    <h2>Documents Required for FSSAI Registration & License</h2>

    <p>The document requirements vary based on the license type. Prepare these in advance to avoid delays in processing.</p>

    <h3>Documents for Basic Registration (All Food Businesses Under ₹12L Turnover)</h3>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Photo identity proof</strong> of the applicant (Aadhaar Card, PAN Card, Voter ID, or Passport)</li>
      <li><strong>Passport-size photograph</strong> of the applicant</li>
      <li><strong>Proof of address</strong> of the business premises (electricity bill, rent agreement, or property tax receipt)</li>
      <li><strong>Self-declaration</strong> regarding food safety and hygiene (provided in the FoSCoS form)</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Documents for State License</h3>

    <p>In addition to the basic documents, a State License application requires:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Photo identity proof</strong> of the proprietor / partners / directors</li>
      <li><strong>Passport-size photograph</strong> of the authorised signatory</li>
      <li><strong>Business entity proof:</strong> Partnership deed, Certificate of Incorporation (for Pvt. Ltd.), LLP agreement, or sole proprietorship declaration</li>
      <li><strong>Proof of possession of premises:</strong> Rent agreement (registered or notarised) or ownership documents</li>
      <li><strong>Food safety management plan:</strong> An outline of your food safety procedures — raw material sourcing, storage, preparation, and hygiene protocols</li>
      <li><strong>Layout plan / blueprint</strong> of the food processing or kitchen area showing equipment placement, ventilation, water supply, and drainage</li>
      <li><strong>List of food products</strong> you intend to manufacture, store, or sell</li>
      <li><strong>NOC (No Objection Certificate)</strong> from the local municipality or panchayat</li>
      <li><strong>Water test report</strong> from an accredited laboratory (confirming potability of water used in food preparation)</li>
      <li><strong>List of equipment and machinery</strong> installed in the premises</li>
      <li><strong>Analysis report of the food products</strong> (for manufacturers — not always required for restaurants)</li>
      <li><strong>Source of raw materials:</strong> Names and addresses of suppliers</li>
      <li><strong>Recall plan:</strong> Documented procedure for recalling products if a safety issue is identified</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Additional Documents for Central License</h3>

    <ul>
      <li>All documents required for State License, plus:</li>
      <li><strong>IEC (Import Export Code)</strong> — for food importers/exporters</li>
      <li><strong>Ministry of Commerce Certificate</strong> — for 100% EOUs</li>
      <li><strong>NOC from the manufacturer</strong> — if you are a re-packer or re-labeller</li>
      <li><strong>Certificate from Ministry of Tourism</strong> — for heritage hotel operators</li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>Pro tip:</strong> Get your water test report done early. It takes 3–7 days from sample collection to report generation, and many applications stall because the applicant has not arranged this in advance. Use an NABL-accredited laboratory.</p>

